      "type": "outpatient",
      "patient_reported_reason": "Worsening breathlessness and increased sputum production over 5 days",
      "clinician_notes": "Subjective: 58-year-old male ex-smoker (stopped 2020, 30 pack-year history) with known GOLD 2 COPD. Presents with 5-day history of increased dyspnoea, increased sputum volume, change in sputum colour from white to yellow-green. No fever. Using reliever inhaler more frequently than usual (Ventolin).\n\nObjective: RR 20/min, SpO2 91% on RA, T 37.1 C, HR 88 bpm, BP 142/88 mmHg. Widespread expiratory wheeze bilaterally. Hyperinflated chest. Peak flow 210 L/min (55% predicted). CXR: hyperinflation, no consolidation.\n\nAssessment: Acute exacerbation of COPD — moderate severity (Anthonisen criteria: increased dyspnoea, increased sputum volume, purulent sputum).\n\nPlan: Doxycycline 200 mg stat then 100 mg OD for 5 days. Prednisolone 30 mg OD for 5 days. Increase Ventolin to 4-6 puffs every 4 hours. Continue tiotropium. Review in 48 hours. Safety-net: return if SpO2 drops below 88%.",
      "diagnoses": [
        {
          "code_system": "ICD-10", "code": "J44.1",
